import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load the dataset
file_path = 'NBA_Player_Statistics_Source.csv'  # Replace with the correct file path
data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# 1. Bar Chart: Average Points_Per_Game by Team
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='Team', y='Points_Per_Game', data=data, errorbar=None)
plt.title('Average Points_Per_Game by Team')
plt.xlabel('Team')
plt.ylabel('Points_Per_Game')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 2. Scatter Plot: Minutes_Per_Game vs Points_Per_Game, categorized by Position
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Minutes_Per_Game', y='Points_Per_Game', data=data, hue='Position', alpha=0.7)
plt.title('Scatter Plot: Minutes_Per_Game vs Points_Per_Game')
plt.xlabel('Minutes_Per_Game')
plt.ylabel('Points_Per_Game')
plt.legend(title='Position')
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 3. Line Chart: Trend of Performance_Level Across Games_Played
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(data['Team'], data['Performance_Level'], marker='o', label='Performance_Level')
plt.title('Trend of Performance_Level Across Teams')
plt.xlabel('Team')
plt.ylabel('Performance_Level')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 4. Histogram: Distribution of Rebounds_Per_Game
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(data['Rebounds_Per_Game'], bins=15, kde=True, color='blue')
plt.title('Distribution of Rebounds_Per_Game')
plt.xlabel('Rebounds_Per_Game')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 5. Box Plot: Blocks_Per_Game by Steals_Per_Game
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='Steals_Per_Game', y='Blocks_Per_Game', data=data)
plt.title('Box Plot of Blocks_Per_Game by Steals_Per_Game')
plt.xlabel('Steals_Per_Game')
plt.ylabel('Blocks_Per_Game')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 6. Pie Chart: Proportion of Turnovers_Per_Game
category_counts = data['Turnovers_Per_Game'].value_counts()
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.pie(category_counts, labels=category_counts.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140)
plt.title('Proportion of Turnovers_Per_Game')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  1. Bar Chart: Average Points_Per_Game by Team
  2. Scatter Plot: Minutes_Per_Game vs Points_Per_Game, categorized by Position
  3. Line Chart: Trend of Performance_Level Across Games_Played
  4. Histogram: Distribution of Rebounds_Per_Game
  5. Box Plot: Blocks_Per_Game by Steals_Per_Game
  6. Pie Chart: Proportion of Turnovers_Per_Game
  1. The average points per game is about 17-23 points. The Celtics have the highest average points per game, which is about 23.
  2. Depending on the points and the position per game the points vary. Towards the end of the game, the Forward position seems to be popular.
  3. The line chart is all over the place. The teams seem to be correlated between each other and the performance level.
  4. The number of rebounds per game is very frequent. Typically lingering from 15-22 is about the average.
  5. The distribution of Blocks per Game appears consistent across most bins of Steals per Game.
  6. The likelihood that there will be a 4.2 pt turnover will be about 4% making it the most likely to happen.
